1 Introduction
**************

1.1 What is Ollama Buddy?
=========================

Ollama Buddy is an Emacs package that provides a friendly AI assistant
interface to Ollama, a tool for running large language models (LLMs)
locally on your computer.  It allows you to interact with AI models
directly from within Emacs for various tasks such as:

   ‚Ä¢ Code refactoring and explanation
   ‚Ä¢ Writing assistance and proofreading
   ‚Ä¢ Generating Git commit messages
   ‚Ä¢ Dictionary lookups and language assistance
   ‚Ä¢ Custom AI-powered workflows via roles
   ‚Ä¢ Using pre-built prompt templates from Fabric
   ‚Ä¢ Utilizing Awesome ChatGPT Prompts
   ‚Ä¢ Integrating with commercial APIs (OpenAI, Claude, Gemini, Grok,
     Copilot, Codestral)
   ‚Ä¢ Using Ollama cloud models
   ‚Ä¢ Including files as context in conversations
   ‚Ä¢ Real-time web search to provide current information to LLMs

   Instead of context-switching to web interfaces or terminal
applications, Ollama Buddy brings the power of local LLMs right into
your Emacs workflow.

1.2 Why Use Ollama Buddy?
=========================

   ‚Ä¢ *Privacy*: All interactions happen locally with Ollama - no data
     sent to external services unless you use commercial APIs
   ‚Ä¢ *Integration*: Seamlessly fits into your existing Emacs workflow
   ‚Ä¢ *Flexibility*: Supports multiple models, parameter tuning, and
     custom commands
   ‚Ä¢ *Efficiency*: Quick access to AI assistance without leaving your
     editor
   ‚Ä¢ *Extensibility*: Create custom roles and commands for your specific
     needs
   ‚Ä¢ *File Support*: Include text files, code, and documentation
     directly in conversations

1.3 Prerequisites
=================

Before using Ollama Buddy, you need:

   ‚Ä¢ Emacs 28.1 or later
   ‚Ä¢ Ollama installed and running on your system (see
     <https://ollama.ai>)
   ‚Ä¢ At least one language model pulled into Ollama
   ‚Ä¢ (Optional) API keys for OpenAI or Claude if you want to use those
     services


