14.2 Role File Naming Convention
================================

The file naming convention is critical to understand how roles, preset
files, and menu configurations work together:

Required filename format
     ‚Äòollama-buddy--preset__ROLE-NAME.el‚Äô
        ‚Ä¢ The double underscore ‚Äò__‚Äô separates the prefix from your role
          name
        ‚Ä¢ The role name portion becomes the identifier shown when
          switching roles
        ‚Ä¢ Example: ‚Äòollama-buddy--preset__programmer.el‚Äô creates a role
          named "programmer"

   This naming convention is how Ollama Buddy discovers and identifies
role files.  When you run ‚Äòollama-buddy-roles-switch-role‚Äô, the system:

  1. Scans the ‚Äòollama-buddy-roles-directory‚Äô for files matching the
     pattern
  2. Extracts the role name from each filename (the part after ‚Äò__‚Äô)
  3. Presents these names in the role selection interface
  4. When selected, loads the corresponding file which redefines
     ‚Äòollama-buddy-command-definitions‚Äô
  5. This redefinition immediately changes the available commands in
     your Ollama Buddy menu

   The relationship chain works like this:
     ollama-buddy--preset__ROLE-NAME.el ‚Üí Defines ollama-buddy-command-definitions ‚Üí Controls menu content

   When creating roles using the interactive role creator (‚ÄòC-c E‚Äô),
this naming convention is automatically handled for you.  When creating
roles manually, you must follow this pattern for Ollama Buddy to
recognize your role files correctly.

