22 Frequently Asked Questions
*****************************

22.1 General Questions
======================

22.1.1 What is the difference between Ollama Buddy and other AI assistants?
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Ollama Buddy integrates with Ollama to run LLMs locally, offering
privacy, customization, and seamless Emacs integration without relying
on external API services.

22.1.2 Does Ollama Buddy require an internet connection?
--------------------------------------------------------

For local Ollama models, no internet connection is required after
pulling them.  Internet is needed for:
   ‚Ä¢ Pulling new models from Ollama
   ‚Ä¢ Using Ollama cloud models
   ‚Ä¢ Using remote providers (OpenAI, Claude, Gemini, Grok, Codestral)
   ‚Ä¢ Syncing Fabric patterns or Awesome ChatGPT Prompts

22.1.3 How do I use Ollama cloud models?
----------------------------------------

Cloud models require authentication:
  1. Run ‚ÄòM-x ollama-buddy-cloud-signin‚Äô to sign in
  2. Select cloud models with ‚ÄòC-u C-c m‚Äô
  3. The ‚Äò‚òÅ‚Äô symbol in the header indicates cloud model usage

22.1.4 Which models work best with Ollama Buddy?
------------------------------------------------

Most models supported by Ollama work well.  Popular choices include:
   ‚Ä¢ llama3:latest - Good general purpose assistant
   ‚Ä¢ codellama:latest - Excellent for code-related tasks
   ‚Ä¢ mistral:latest - Good balance of performance and quality
   ‚Ä¢ phi:latest - Smaller model that works well on limited hardware

22.1.5 How much RAM do I need?
------------------------------

It depends on the model:
   ‚Ä¢ Small models (7B) - 8GB minimum, 16GB recommended
   ‚Ä¢ Medium models (13B) - 16GB minimum, 24GB+ recommended
   ‚Ä¢ Large models (34B+) - 32GB+ recommended

   Quantized models (e.g., Q4_K_M variants) require less RAM.

22.2 Usage Questions
====================

22.2.1 How do I cancel a request that's taking too long?
--------------------------------------------------------

Press ‚ÄòC-c k‚Äô in the chat buffer or select "Kill Request" from the menu.

22.2.2 How can I save my conversations?
---------------------------------------

Use ‚ÄòC-c S‚Äô to save the current session, giving it a name.  You can
restore it later with ‚ÄòC-c L‚Äô.

22.2.3 Can I use multiple models in the same conversation?
----------------------------------------------------------

Yes, you can switch models at any time with ‚ÄòC-c m‚Äô.  Each model
maintains its own conversation history.

22.2.4 How do I clear the conversation history?
-----------------------------------------------

Press ‚ÄòC-c X‚Äô to clear history, or ‚ÄòC-c N‚Äô to start a completely new
session.

22.2.5 How can I create a custom command?
-----------------------------------------

The easiest way is through the role creator: press ‚ÄòC-c E‚Äô and follow
the prompts to create commands with specific prompts, models, and
parameters.

22.2.6 How can I manage context windows?
----------------------------------------

Ollama Buddy provides several options:
   ‚Ä¢ Enable context monitoring with ‚Äò(setq
     ollama-buddy-show-context-percentage t)‚Äô
   ‚Ä¢ Use ‚ÄòC-c C‚Äô to check current context usage
   ‚Ä¢ Limit history length with ‚ÄòC-c Y‚Äô
   ‚Ä¢ Set model-specific context sizes with ‚ÄòC-c $‚Äô

22.2.7 What happens when I exceed the context limit?
----------------------------------------------------

When context monitoring is enabled:
   ‚Ä¢ You'll get a warning when approaching the limit (85-100%)
   ‚Ä¢ You'll get an error dialog at or above 100%
   ‚Ä¢ You can choose to proceed anyway or modify your content

22.2.8 How do I create effective system prompts?
------------------------------------------------

Effective system prompts typically include:
   ‚Ä¢ Clear role definition for the AI
   ‚Ä¢ Specific guidelines for response format and style
   ‚Ä¢ Examples of desired output (when applicable)
   ‚Ä¢ Constraints or limitations to observe
   Start simple, test the response, and refine iteratively.

22.2.9 Where are my system prompts stored?
------------------------------------------

System prompts are stored as .org files in the directory specified by
'ollama-buddy-user-prompts-directory', which defaults to
'~/.emacs.d/ollama-buddy-user-prompts/'.

22.3 Troubleshooting
====================

22.3.1 Ollama Buddy shows "OFFLINE" status
------------------------------------------

Ensure that:
   ‚Ä¢ Ollama is installed and running
   ‚Ä¢ The hostname and port are correctly configured (‚Äòollama-buddy-host‚Äô
     and ‚Äòollama-buddy-port‚Äô)
   ‚Ä¢ Your firewall isn't blocking connections

22.3.2 Responses are slow or the model seems to hang
----------------------------------------------------

Try:
   ‚Ä¢ Using a smaller model
   ‚Ä¢ Adjusting the ‚Äònum_ctx‚Äô parameter to a smaller value
   ‚Ä¢ Setting ‚Äòlow_vram‚Äô to ‚Äòt‚Äô if you have limited GPU memory
   ‚Ä¢ Checking CPU/RAM usage to ensure your system isn't overloaded

22.3.3 Getting "error parsing model" when pulling a model
---------------------------------------------------------

This usually means:
   ‚Ä¢ The model name is incorrect
   ‚Ä¢ The model is not available in the Ollama repository
   ‚Ä¢ You have network connectivity issues

22.3.4 Model responses are low quality or truncated
---------------------------------------------------

Try:
   ‚Ä¢ Increasing the ‚Äòtemperature‚Äô parameter for more creative responses
   ‚Ä¢ Increasing ‚Äònum_predict‚Äô for longer responses
   ‚Ä¢ Using a more capable model
   ‚Ä¢ Providing clearer instructions in your prompt

22.3.5 How do system prompts differ from regular prompts?
---------------------------------------------------------

System prompts provide overall instructions to the AI about its role and
how to respond, while regular prompts are your specific questions or
requests.  System prompts persist across the conversation, affecting all
responses, while regular prompts are one-time interactions.

22.3.6 What is the global system prompt?
----------------------------------------

The global system prompt is a baseline prompt automatically prepended to
all requests.  It's useful for consistent formatting instructions across
all models.  Toggle it with ‚ÄòM-x
ollama-buddy-toggle-global-system-prompt‚Äô.

22.3.7 How do I use image analysis/vision features?
---------------------------------------------------

  1. Select a vision-capable model (e.g., gemma3:4b, llama3.2:3b)
  2. Include an image path in your prompt
  3. The image will be automatically detected and encoded

   Supported formats: PNG, JPG, JPEG, WebP, GIF.

22.3.8 Can I share system prompts between different installations?
------------------------------------------------------------------

Yes, the user system prompts are stored as plain text .org files in your
'ollama-buddy-user-prompts-directory'.  You can copy these files to
share them with colleagues or between different machines.


